  <h1>Optic Disc Localization in Fundus Images</h1>

  <p><strong>Role:</strong> Sole Developer</p>

  <h2>Project Description</h2>
  <p>
    This project focuses on accurately detecting the optic disc center in retinal
    fundus images using classical computer vision techniques. The pipeline is designed
    to be robust against illumination variations and anatomical differences.
  </p>

  <p>
    Blood vessels are first extracted using adaptive mean thresholding with dynamically
    adjusted kernel sizes. Bright candidate regions are then isolated using iterative
    thresholding, and multiple masks are combined using bitwise operations to localize
    the optic disc precisely.
  </p>

  <h2>Methodology</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Blood vessel extraction using adaptive mean thresholding (kernel sizes 15√ó15 to 71√ó71)</li>
    <li>Bright region detection with auto-adjusted thresholding (starting T = 200)</li>
    <li>Mask fusion using bitwise operations</li>
    <li>Optic disc center localization</li>
    <li>Error evaluation using Euclidean distance</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Results</h2>
  <p>
    The system achieves low-error optic disc localization, with a sample mean deviation
    of <strong>8.7 pixels</strong> from ground truth centers.
  </p>

  <h2>Skills & Deliverables</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Computer Vision</li>
    <li>Machine Learning</li>
    <li>Python</li>
    <li>OpenCV</li>
    <li>NumPy</li>
  </ul>

